time";i:1599273966;}i:68;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:2149:"Hello friends. I just finished this book and I had to share you my review. 
.

I received this book today from my Book of The Month subscription, and I immediately wanted to start it because the cover captivated my attention so much. It is the story of Gifty, who is a sixth-year candidate in neuroscience at Stanford University School of Medicine. Her project consists of studying the behavior of mice and the neural circuits of depression and addiction. Her brother, Nana, was a very talented athlete who unfortunately lost his life after an overdose of heroin. Before this, Nana had an accident that damaged his ankle, so he was taking OxyContin. Gifty's mother, traumatized by the situation, is in bed, in total depression. Gifty, on the other hand, is determined to discover the scientific basis for the suffering she sees in the people around her. This scientific investigation to solve the mystery of her family loss will not be easy. She will have to analyze her beliefs. When she was a girl, she used to go to the evangelical church with her mother. Faith has been instilled deeply in her. It is a very challenging investigation, but it is something Gifty has to figure out to be at peace. I loved this book more than a story, it is an analysis of today's society. Gifty is the daughter of immigrants who came to the United States in search of a better life. The situations they naturally experienced were a bit complicated. Suffering is not something easy to explain, and I like that the author has told this story mentioning elements of faith and society that affect people every day. It is a gem of a book that I read in a single sitting, and that left me meditating to write this review.
.
What book did you get for BOTM?
.

